## OUTPUT — WRITE VERDICT WITH PER-ITEM RUBRIC

You MUST score the upstream output with a rubric applied **per item**,
not just per output. Every keyword, person, model, topic, citation,
synthesis page (etc.) gets its own `item_verdict` with per-dimension
scores. Whole-output dimensions (e.g. deduplication, count) are
emitted as item_verdicts with `target=null`.

### Step 1 — declare your rubric in `_rubric`

For every numbered verification criterion in the section above, add a
`_rubric` entry. Use the bold header (snake_case) as the key and
copy a short description of the criterion as the value. Example:

    _rubric:
      relevance:    "Item is a distinctive concept the source uses or introduces."
      no_fabrication: "No claims that aren't backed by source evidence."

This block is consumed by downstream tasks so they understand the
scoring axes without re-reading your prompt.

### Step 2 — score every item

Walk the upstream output:

- For list-shaped outputs (keywords, people, models, topics,
  citations, synthesis_pages, etc.): emit ONE `item_verdict` per
  item, with `target=<item.name>` matching the upstream name
  verbatim. Score every applicable rubric dimension on that item.

- For single-object outputs (classify's quintet, summary's text):
  emit ONE `item_verdict` with `target=null`, scoring every rubric
  dimension on the whole output.

- Per-output dimensions (e.g. `deduplication`, `count`,
  `failed_kinds_correctness`): emit additional `target=null`
  entries scoring just those dimensions.

For each `item_verdict`:

- `verdict` — derive from this item's scores: any `FAIL` → REJECT,
  otherwise any `REVIEW` → REVIEW, otherwise ACCEPT.
- `scores` — `{<dimension>: PASS|REVIEW|FAIL}`. Keys MUST be names
  declared in `_rubric`.
- `rationale` — cite concrete evidence (quoted source passage,
  named field). Do not score by gut.

### Step 3 — derive the overall verdict

The top-level `verdict` follows from `item_verdicts`:

| Worst per-item verdict          | Overall |
|---------------------------------|---------|
| Any entry with `verdict=REJECT` | REJECT  |
| Else any `verdict=REVIEW`       | REVIEW  |
| All `verdict=ACCEPT`            | ACCEPT  |

Inconsistency between item_verdicts and the overall verdict is a
malformed verdict.

### Step 4 — write the `reasoning` field

A one-paragraph (≥30 char) summary naming the item_verdicts that
drove the overall verdict. Example: "Per-item: 'Emil Stenström'
verdict=REJECT (no_fabrication FAIL — name not in source body)
drives overall REJECT; remaining people ACCEPT."

### Build the verdict file

The verdict output target is:

    {{ verdict_path }}

The agent output you are judging lives at:

    {{ output_path }}

DO NOT use ``fs_write`` to write the verdict file directly.

#### 1. Initialize

    curator.sh builders init {{ verdict_path }} --schema judge

#### 2. Set ALL required fields in a single ``add`` call

The schema requires `_rubric` (≥1 dimension), `verdict`, `reasoning`,
and `item_verdicts` (≥1 entry). Validation runs after each ``add``,
so a partial add will be rejected. Bundle every rubric definition,
the top-level fields, AND your item_verdicts into one ``add``:

    curator.sh builders add {{ verdict_path }} \
        --set _rubric.<dim_a>='<description>' \
        --set _rubric.<dim_b>='<description>' \
        --set _rubric.<dim_c>='<description>' \
        --set verdict=<ACCEPT|REVIEW|REJECT> \
        --set reasoning='<≥30-char summary citing item_verdicts>' \
        --set item_verdicts.0.target='<item-name-or-null>' \
        --set item_verdicts.0.verdict=<ACCEPT|REVIEW|REJECT> \
        --set item_verdicts.0.scores.<dim_a>=<PASS|REVIEW|FAIL> \
        --set item_verdicts.0.scores.<dim_b>=<PASS|REVIEW|FAIL> \
        --set item_verdicts.0.rationale='<evidence-cited explanation>' \
        --set item_verdicts.1.target='<next-item>' \
        --set item_verdicts.1.verdict=<ACCEPT|REVIEW|REJECT> \
        --set item_verdicts.1.scores.<dim_a>=<PASS|REVIEW|FAIL> \
        --set item_verdicts.1.scores.<dim_b>=<PASS|REVIEW|FAIL> \
        --set item_verdicts.1.rationale='<...>' \
        # ... repeat for every item

For target=null, set the literal `null`:

    --set item_verdicts.<i>.target=null

For long item lists you may split into multiple ``add`` calls AFTER
the first call has satisfied all required fields — each subsequent
call appends additional item_verdicts indices.

For an all-PASS rubric, the `issues` array stays empty. Use it only
for auxiliary signals that don't fit per-item.
